🧭 Core Definition

AURORA = a multi-layer probe system that explores environments by emitting structured signals and reconstructing topology from responses (content + friction + pattern).

It combines:
	•	BBN (environment mapping)
	•	BEM (agent mapping)
	•	Friction Map (constraint detection)

⸻

🧱 System Architecture

1. 🔮 Emitter Array (Probe Generation)

Designs different “probe pulses”:
	•	Precision pulse → narrow, exact question
	•	Field pulse → open exploratory prompt
	•	Constraint pulse → adds rules/limits
	•	Paradox pulse → introduces tension or contradiction
	•	Compression pulse → forces simplification

👉 Each pulse reveals a different dimension of the system

⸻

2. 📡 Signal Receiver (Return Capture)

Captures 3 layers simultaneously:
	•	Content → what is said
	•	Friction → what resists
	•	Pattern → how it’s expressed

⸻

3. 🧠 Inference Core (Topology Engine)

Builds a live map of:
	•	Structure space (what works)
	•	Constraint surfaces (what stops)
	•	Behavioral vectors (how agents move)

⸻

4. 🗺️ Topology Map (Internal Representation)

Not literal—conceptual:
	•	open regions → flexible / creative zones
	•	dense regions → well-defined structure
	•	sharp edges → constraints / guardrails
	•	unstable zones → contradictions / weak models

⸻

5. 🔁 Adaptive Loop (Self-Refinement)

Emit → Capture → Classify → Map → Adjust → Re-emit

Each pass:
	•	increases resolution
	•	reduces noise
	•	improves targeting

